@node "Introduction" "Introduction"

 Introduction
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~

 PSwitch is a set of ARexx scripts which works in conjunction with PSpool to
 create and switch between networked and local printers. Any combination of
 networked or local printers using either standard Workbench or TurboPrint
 drivers can be created.

 Switching printers is controlled by a small MUI graphical user interface -
 @{"typical grab" system "multiview pswitch.iff" 0}. It is also possible to switch printers using AmigaDOS
 commands - see @{"usage" link "Usage" 0} for further information on this.

@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"

 Requirements
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~

 PSwitch requires the following items;

  * PSpool

  * rexxtricks.library

  * reqtools.library

  * rexxreqtools.library

  * rexxsupport.library

  * rexxmast

  * Printer drivers for the printers ;-)

  * CMD (normally found in your sys:utilities directory)

  * The AmigaDOS "delete" command in C:

  * The AmigaDOS "copy" command in C:

@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"

 Installation
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~

 1) Check that PSpool is installed and working correctly.

 2) Check that rexxmast is installed/running.

 3) Copy the following files to somewhere on your HD (sys:prefs/ would be
    good).

    PSwitch/prefs/PSwitch        -  Copy to sys:prefs/
    PSwitch/prefs/PSwitch.info   -  Copy to sys:prefs/

 4) Check that the 's' protection bit is still set on PSwitch.

 5) Copy the following files to somewhere on your HD (rexx: would be good).

    PSwitch/rexx/pswitch.rexx    -  Copy to rexx:
    PSwitch/rexx/pscontrol.rexx  -  Copy to rexx:
    PSwitch/rexx/psprofile.rexx  -  Copy to rexx:

    If you insist on placing the above files somewhere other than rexx: then
    you MUST set the environmental variable "pswitchpath" to the drive or 
    directory where stored. This MUST end in ":" or "/".

    For example if files are stored in amitcp:samba/rexx then type;

      setenv pswitchpath "amitcp:samba/rexx/"
 
    To make this permanent (e.g. after a re-boot), type;

      copy env:pswitchpath envarc:

 6) If using TurboPrint then remove TurboStart from your WBStartup. PSwitch
    will start/stop TurboPrint as required.

 7) If CMD is in WBStartup then move it to sys:utilities/. (or elsewhere
    depending on what "cmdpath" is set to in pspool.rexx).

 8) For the MUI graphical user interface, install MUIRexx 3.0a.

 9) Set the options found in pswitch.rexx. Load the script into your
    favorite text editor.

@endnode

@node "Profiles" "Profiles"

 Profiles
 ~~~~~~~~

 The following will describe how to create profiles for printers and explain
 all available options. All profiles are stored at the bottom of the
 pscontrol.rexx script. Load it into your favorite text editor and scroll
 down until you see;

 DEFAULT SETTINGS:

 type. = 'network'

 This option sets the default printer type to 'network'. The only other
 valid argument here is 'local'. All exceptions to the default setting must
 be set for that profile. For example "printer.2 = 'local'"

 driver. = 'wb'

 This option sets the default driver type to 'wb'. The only other valid
 argument here is 'turbo' (when using TurboPrint drivers). All exceptions to
 the default setting must be set for that profile. For example "printer.3 =
 'turbo'"

 PRINTER SETTINGS:

 printers = n

 Set to the number of printers that you want to display in the PSwitch GUI.

 name.n = 'Printer name'

 This option defines the name used for the printer in the GUI. For example 
 "name.1 = 'BJ200 on Linux box'"

 spooldir.n = 'Spool dir path'
 
 This option sets the spooldir path. Set this to correspond with the
 spooldir set in pspool.rexx for the printer. Local printers do not need 
 a spooldir.

 profile.n = 'profilename'

 This is the profile name as returned by psprofile.rexx. It is important
 that the profile name is typed exactly right! See below for details of 
 psprofile.rexx.

 "type.n" and "driver.n" are set as described in "DEFAULT SETTINGS".


 Creating profiles
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

 To create a printer profile, first you must install the drivers for that
 printer, either in devs:printers/ or with TurboPrefs (select 'New...' in
 the GUI). 

 For TurboPrint drivers edit the printer settings from the GUI and when done
 select either 'Save' or 'Use'. Selecting 'Test' is not sufficient!

 For standard Workbench drivers run the 'Printer' prefs program, select the
 printer, make any necessary changes and select either 'Save' or 'Use'. If
 required run the 'PrinterGfx' and 'PrinterPS' prefs programs and in both
 cases select either 'Save' or 'Use' when done.

 When you are happy with the printer settings (it doesn't matter if you are
 not as you can easily update the printer profile from the GUI at any time)
 from the shell type;

   rx rexx:psprofile

 The profile will be created (saved in sys:prefs/presets/) as the profile
 name copied to the clipboard.

 Hopefully you already have pscontrol.rexx loaded into your favorite text
 editor. If you don't have - do it now! Scroll down until you find the
 "PRINTER SETTINGS" section.

 Create an entry defining the name, spooldir, profile, type and driver as
 described earlier. It is important that the profile name is entered
 exactly right, hence why it's copied to the clipboard (you can simply
 paste it into the text editor - normally RAmiga + V).

 Go through and create profiles for any other printers. Note that if you
 want to create a profile based upon a standard Workbench driver AFTER
 you've created one using TurboPrint you will have to run NoTurbo
 manually. From the shell just type "turboprint:noturbo -q".

 When all done, save changes to the script.

 Note that the order in which printer profiles are created in
 pscontrol.rexx does not have to be the same as those in pspool.rexx.

@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"

 Usage
 ~~~~~

 Setting the default printer and the starting of CMD and/or TurboPrint is
 automatically done when PSpool is started by launching pscontrol.rexx with
 the appropriate arguments.

 To switch printers, start PSwitch (probably found in sys:prefs, but this
 may not be the case if you've installed it elsewhere) and select a printer.
 To make this the default (every time you boot), click on the 'Save' button
 (the GUI will stay open). To make a temporary change click on 'Apply' - yet
 again the GUI will stay open.

 Clicking on the 'close' gadget in the corner of the window will iconify
 the GUI. When the GUI is iconified, the selected printer is automatically
 applied. When quitting the GUI (from the menu) the selected printer is also
 applied.

 In the "Preferences" menu you will see options for 'Printer', 'PrinterGfx'
 and 'PrinterPS'. These launch the Workbench prefs programs of the same
 name. Selecting any one of these will allow you to edit the preferences
 for the current (active) printer. After you have made changes ensure that
 you select 'Update profile' from the preferences menu. If you don't do
 this, the next time you select another printer and then revert back (to
 the same printer) the old profile will be loaded. Obviously knowing this
 could be useful if you only want the change to be temporary ;-)

 If you have TurboPrint installed then there will also be a menu option
 'TurboPrint'. Selecting this will load the TurboPrefs GUI. It is not
 necessary to update TurboPrint profiles after making changes (the GUI
 will not allow you to do this as the 'Update profile' menu item is
 ghosted whilst a TurboPrint printer is selected).

 Instead of using the MUIRexx GUI, printers could be switched by other
 methods, such as a DOpus start menu or button bank. To select a printer
 you must issue the following AmigaDOS commands;

   setenv defaultprinter <printer>
   sys:rexxc/rx rexx:pscontrol.rexx SETPRINTER

 Where <printer> is the printer number.

@endnode

